handling**\\n\\nI'm thinking about handling ExceptionInInitializerError. For native methods, maybe we've generated metadata that allows dynamic access. I wonder if we could assert the cause. If findSource returns null due to being inaccessible, we could catch the exception and proceed. But then, if the class is marked erroneous, that's only one test. After merging metadata in a native context, I might find that findSource can succeed. It’s a bit complex!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering mapping options**\\n\\nI’m thinking about one-to-one mapping, but it might be tricky with test class files. Helpers could count as class files rather than generated test classes, so I should probably avoid that if possible. I can’t use the JDK package, but I'm wondering if I could use Conscrypt names instead. Packages like com.android.org.conscrypt or org.conscrypt seem available. I could create helper Provider/SecureRandomSpi classes under org.conscrypt, which feels like a less complicated option.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering nonce and IV use**\\n\\nI'm exploring whether I could use Nonce and IV. If they are both set to default, then perhaps the Nonce wouldn't matter, but I'm not completely sure. It sounds like I might need to acquire some value for \\\"NONCEANDIV\\\". However, if both have already been initialized from earlier tests, it seems I can't access that option. This is a bit confusing, and I want to make sure I approach this correctly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_B2YMuPbIVwCa5ZWjjK4jdovJ|fc_087817b68d3376ff0169fbe6d9063481a1882749c3db3efd6d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"SecureRandom\\.DEFAULT\\|NONCEANDIV\\|DRBG\\|BouncyCastleProvider\" -n tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15to18/1.77/src/test/java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 929, "output": 1618, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 28147, "cost": {"input": 0, 